<HEAD>Portrait Painted One Month Before Artist's Suicide Goes On Sale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A month before he killed himself, <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> painted a portrait in blue of his innkeeper's young daughter. The girl, <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravoux </PERSON>, 13, was on the terrace of the cafe in <LOCATION> Auvers </LOCATION>, a village outside <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, when the artist returned from the fields, his hands pressed to the bullet wound in his stomach. Two days later, July 29, 1890, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> died. He was 37 years old. On Wednesday, `` Portrait of <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravoux </PERSON>'' will offered for sale at an auction of impressionist and modern paintings. <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s, the auction house, estimates that it will fetch more than $ 15 million. Experts say interest in the portrait is keen in part because of the story behind it. The adolescent girl who posed for the painting said in an essay published in 1956 that she considered it `` somewhat of a disappointment'' at first. But in her later years, <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravoux </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> said she finally came to appreciate its insight into her character. Mrs. <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> described <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, who lived at her father's inn during the last 2 -LCB- months of his life, as a disciplined artist and `` a soft and calm'' man who always smoked a pipe and enjoyed playing with her little sister. She also recalled the last two days of the artist's life during which he slowly succumbed to the fatal bullet. A doctor came to dress the wound, police officers arrived to investigate the suicide and the artist's brother <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> arrived running from the train station, his face `` distorted by grief,'' she wrote. The portrait being auctioned Wednesday is one of three versions van <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> painted. When last offered for sale, in 1980 at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, it brought $ 1.98 million from an anonymous buyer. Last year, three of <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s paintings fetched record multimillion - dollar prices that shocked the art world The artist sold almost nothing during his lifetime. In March 1987, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Sunflowers'' sold for $ 39.9 million at <ORGANIZATION> Christie </ORGANIZATION>'s in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a Japanese firm, <ORGANIZATION> Yasuda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Three months later, `` The Trinquetaille Bridge'' went for $ 20.2 million, also at <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> It was bought by an unidentified collector living in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Then in November, history was made when <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' _ a richly-colored composition of purple flowers and green leaves set off by a single white iris _ sold at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for $ 53.9 million to an anonymous buyer. It was the highest price paid at auction for any painting. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rewald </PERSON>, the author of `` Post-Impressionism: From van <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> to <PERSON> Gauguin </PERSON>,'' has said of `` Irises'': `` If a museum could have one painting by <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, that's what it should get.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Findlay </PERSON>, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s senior vice president, said he did n't think `` Portrait of <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravoux </PERSON>'' would bring anywhere near the price paid for `` Irises.'' The special appeal of the portrait, aside from the painting itself, is its link to <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s last days, said <PERSON> Findlay </PERSON>. In the painting, <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON>, dressed in blue, sits in profile on a chair. Her blond hair is tied with a blue ribbon, her gaze is serene, her posture correct and her hands folded demurely in front of her. `` He observed her very deeply, and when he came to paint her, he painted both the grace and stiff awkwardness of an adolescent girl,'' <PERSON> Findlay </PERSON> said. He used `` brief flashing strokes'' and `` astonishing'' color; the background is `` almost an electric blue, a night blue,'' he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON>, who died in 1965 at age 88, had written: `` I admit that I was only moderately satisfied with my portrait; it was somewhat of a disappointment, for I did not find it was true to life.'' But she also told an interviewer, `` <PERSON> Monsieur </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> divined not the young girl I was, but the woman I was to become.'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> gave the first of his three versions of the portrait to the <PERSON> Ravoux </PERSON> family. More lifelike and detailed than the version up for auction, it is now in a private collection in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. A third version that shows only the face and whose colors are less brilliant is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>.
