s in the 1970s, The Los Angelest Times reported. The ex-general was interviewed Friday and Saturday by <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeper </PERSON>, working on behalf of plaintiffs seeking damages in federal court for victims of the Argentine junta. The junta has been blamed for the deaths of thousands of people. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, 64, said he ordered <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON>'s arrest after a subordinate presented him with accusations that the publisher was `` friends with a man who owned a bank that funded guerrillas,'' the Times quoted the attorney as saying. It was believed to be the first time <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> had acknowledged his role in the arrest of <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON>, who described his imprisonment and torture in the 1981 book `` Prisoner Without A Name, Cell Without A Number.'' The newspaper quoted Ms. <PERSON> Hoeper </PERSON> as saying <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> `` knew <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON> was being interrogated. He said he listened to a tape-recording of an interrogation ...'' The military confiscated <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON>'s newspaper, La Opinion, which campaigned against the junta's anti-Semitic policies. <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON> spent 29 months in jail and under house arrest before being expelled to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, where he became a citizen. <PERSON> Timerman </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> last year and has received $ 5 million from the government as compensation for the loss of his newspaper. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> commanded the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> from 1976 to 1979. He fled the country after a civilian government took over in 1983 and was arrested in January 1987 south of <LOCATION> Sa