<HEAD>Grocery Store Provides Babysitting Service For Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some kids call it the `` grocery-store school'' and some parents call it a godsend. It's a baby-sitting service at the supermarket that lets parents in peace, and leaves more room in the cart for groceries. `` It's definitely helpful, especially when a mother has only two hands and two children and -LRB- is -RRB- trying to grocery shop,'' said 35-year-old <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Redfearn </PERSON>, who drives 17 miles from <LOCATION> Herrin </LOCATION> to shop at the Country Fair store in <LOCATION> Carbondale </LOCATION>. `` It's terrific,'' she said. Located at the front of the Country Fair store, the baby-sitting center has a color TV, a video cassette recorder, a 55-gallon aquarium, two bulletin boards, five bean bags, five plastic trucks and cars and stuffed animals. But if junior still gets bored, there's a 60-piece set of wooden building blocks, a xylophone, an Etch-a-Sketch, a toy telephone and a toy cash register. Safety scissors, glue and paint brushes, crayons, markers and paper complete the picture. The 18-by-16-foot area is a separate room from the store. It has brown carpeted floors and its walls are decorated with drawings by the children. Big windows allow parents to check in on their youngsters while they shop. `` My biggest problem is trying to get the kids to leave on time,'' said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Overstreet </PERSON>, 23, coordinator of the <LOCATION> Carbondale </LOCATION> center. `` They like to go to grocery-store school _ some of the kids call it that.'' The child-care center opened in October and entertained its 6,000 th youngster this past week `` I've had a lot of positive comments from mothers, from customers,'' said store manager <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmutz </PERSON>. `` I've had a lot of older mothers tell me we should've done this 20 years ago.'' `` The kids enjoy themselves more so than they enjoy grocery shopping,'' said 32-year-old <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsh </PERSON> shortly after picking up her year-old daughter at the center. A minimum $ 25 purchase at the store entitles parents to up to two hours of free child care. After two hours, there's a $ 5-an-hour charge. To ensure safety, the same person who checks a child in must check him out, and parents must remain on the store premises while the child is at the center. Children from age six months to six years are accepted. The idea came from <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vernon </LOCATION>, owner of the five Country Fairs in the <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> area. All but one offer the baby-sitting service.
