<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATOKA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The people who moved onto the <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION> late in 1985 made friends easily. Nobody in this rural area where a man's background is his own business questioned their claim to have bought the ranch with an inheritance. But the federal government alleges that the <LOCATION> Atoka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ranch north of <LOCATION> Stringtown </LOCATION> was a cover for laundering more than $ 1 million in proceeds from international drug trafficking by claiming the money came from cattle sales. Federal authorities also allege the isolated 2,889-acre property, since renamed the Junior Ranch, was bought as a refuge for <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> <PERSON> Subias </PERSON>, a Mexican national wanted for questioning in the torture slaying of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent, the killings of nine Venezuelan national guardsmen and the slaying of a Mexican federal police officer. <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> was arrested April 1 in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and is jailed in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Although federal officials now say they had been investigating the southeast <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> ranch for two years, the lid started coming off when two Texans stumbled onto a nearby marijuana-growing operation in August. They accused the owner of that ranch of abduction and details started emerging at the subsequent trial. `` If he does n't bother you, then why bother him? Just because they came in with a lot of money?'' said <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gammon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Atoka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> clerk. When the Mexicans bought the ranch, it was viewed as a logical investment of their money. `` They told us they inherited it. We believed them and we welcomed them to the community,'' said <LOCATION> Atoka </LOCATION> City Manager <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>. `` We are still in shock.'' Residents knew <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> as <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> or <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillen </PERSON>. People interviewed last week said he was a model citizen who made friends easily because of his gentel ways. `` They were planting feed, not dope,'' said a businessman who would talk to a reporter only if his name were not used. `` They came here to make it their home.'' <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> drove a hard bargain and wrote checks for purchases rather than paying cash, the businessman said. Most big-ticket items were financed. `` Does that sound like they were laundering money?'' he asked. But residents reported to be closely associated with <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> now deny knowing him well. People who attended parties at the ranch threaten lawsuits if their names are mentioned in connection with <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>. <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, 42, originally was arrested in 1985 in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> with Mexican drug king <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> is awaiting trial in the 1985 slaying of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> DEA agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>. <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> was sent to jail in <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, to stand trial for the slaying of a Mexican federal agent. But he escaped in October 1985 after bribing his jailers, according to documents filed by <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents. Two months before his escape, a group of Mexicans negotiated to buy the <LOCATION> Atoka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ranch from rancher <PERSON> E.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, at a price of $ 900,000, plus $ 99,000 for