<HEAD>Prominent Psychiatrist Accused Of Unethical Conduct In Fortune
Squabble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> is accused in a probate dispute of exploiting a woman who gave him $ 80,000 a year in trusts and willed $ 5 million to a psychiatric institute she founded during a decade of psychoanalysis with him. The legal battle is between Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s leading psychoanalysts, and <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, only child of <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>, who died in 1984 at age 78 <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> denies any wrongdoing. Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> left most of her estimated $ 5 million estate to a non-profit institute she established four years earlier to promote psychiatric research and music. None of the money has been paid, however, because her son is contesting her will in <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Probate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. A trial is scheduled to begin July 5. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> of improperly using his influence while treating his mother for depression to urge her to create the institute and `` wrongfully inducing'' her to bequeath her fortune to it, according to court documents. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, who was attending the annual meeting of the association in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, referred calls for comment to his attorney, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> said he had advised <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> not to discuss the case. But <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> denied the allegations in an affidavit Dec. 4, 1986. `` I never made false representations to her for the purpose and with the intent of improperly controlling, dominating and misleading her and unduly influencing and wrongfully inducing her to execute her last will,'' <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> said he saw `` no support or substantiation'' for claims that Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> was incompetent or unduly influenced. `` But anyone can file a lawsuit, and these days it has become a recognized means of social expression,'' he added. Dr. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Strasburger </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> psychiatrist who reviewed <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>'s conduct in Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s case at the request of her son's attorneys, contended in a deposition that there were grounds for a malpractice suit. He was paid $ 200 an hour as an expert witness. <PERSON> Strasburger </PERSON> said he reviewed Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s prescription records and found she was taking enough medication to become psychologically and physically addicted. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, who will step down as president when the association's annual meeting ends Thursday, also is director of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychoanalysis </ORGANIZATION> and a <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> conducted up to five sessions a week with Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> from 1969 to 1980, when he transferred her case to two other psychiatrists, saying he needed more time for other professional duties, court documents show. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> continued prescribing medication for her until 1983, and records show he told the succeeding psychiatrists in a letter: `` Incidentally, I do hope that you are charging her a full fee for your housecalls and visits. She can well afford it.'' During the years Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> was a patient of <LOCATION> Pollock </LOCATION>: _ She established a trust fund that has paid <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> $ 50,000 a year since 1976 and will continue paying him through 1993 She established a second trust that has paid <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>'s family $ 30,000 a year since 1978. Court records are n't clear when the second trust expires. _ From 1969 until her death, Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> donated $ 601,330 to the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychoanalysis </ORGANIZATION> Of that money, $ 60,233 went to a depression research fund controlled by <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>. _ In 1980, she created the <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> worked for a short time as a paid consultant to the institute, but said in his affidavit that `` there is no secret agreement'' for him to participate in its future operations. He also denied receiving any benefit from Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s will. _ Mrs <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> dismissed her longtime attorneys when they expressed reservations about her institute and hired <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schanfield </PERSON>, a friend of <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>. _ In 1982, she amended her will to leave $ 200,000 to her son, several thousand dollars to two grandchildren and the rest of her money _ estimated at $ 5 million _ to the <ORGANIZATION> Lederer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> She also named <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, <PERSON> Schanfield </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> as co-executors of her estate. <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s son was worth about $ 2 million before her death and that when she died he inherited about $ 6 million from a trust established by her father, E.J. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>, vice president and comptroller of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the 1930s. The two <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> families are not related. Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> referred to her son's wealth to explain in her last will why she was leaving most of her money `` to my foundation.'' <PERSON> Schanfield </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> told him that he was one of four lawyers referred to her by <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> to review her estate planning and help her establish the research institute. `` Dr. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> played no role whatsoever in establishing that institute,'' <PERSON> Schanfield </PERSON> said Friday in a telephone interview. `` Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> set it up.'' In their briefs, attorneys for Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Murnighan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Doran </PERSON>, suggest she was dependent on <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON>. The attorneys contended that after Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>'s husband, a doctor, died in 1973, `` Dr. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> took the place of her husband and he constantly advised her on all facets of life, from where she was going to live, to what she was going to eat, to what medical treatment to get, to what raises to give the housekeeper.'' <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> were friends, and that the psychiatrist accepted her financial gifts `` because there was no reason not to accept'' them, a point of ethical debate. But <PERSON> Strasburger </PERSON> wrote: `` His acceptance of large gifts to his family, his institution and himself occurred in a pattern of conduct evidencing gross disregard for psychoanalytic principle and psychiatric propriety.'' Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstock </PERSON>, a psychiatrist and associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, said he knew of no specific guidelines on ethics that prohibit psychiatrists from accepting gifts or donations from patients. `` I can say that it would be unusual while somebody is in treatment to accept large gifts,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` It's not standard to do that.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s principles of medical ethics do not contain a specific provision against accepting money or other gifts from patients beyond professional fees. But the principles do say a psychiatrist `` should not use the unique position of power afforded him by the psychotherapeutic situation to influence the patient in any way not directly relevant to the treatment goals.''
