<HEAD>Field Crowded In Many Categories As Tony Award Nominations To Be
Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Tony Awards nominating committee has a happy problem this year, more talent and worthy performances in some categories than can be squeezed into the customary four nominations. Contrary to what has happened in some recent seasons, this year there should be some interesting contests in Broadway's equivalent of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s Oscars. The nominations are due to be announced Monday. The winners of the 42nd annual awards, to be chosen by a vote by more than 600 theater professionals, will be announced June 5 in a program broadcast nationally on CBS. Three plays eligible for `` best play'' <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> contention are by playwrights who have previously won the Pulitzer Prize, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>, August <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. The last play to open before the <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> deadline was <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>'s `` Speed the Plow,'' which got lavish media attention because it stars rock star-actress <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>'s `` Glengarry <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>'' won a Pulitzer in 1984. `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone,'' set early this century, is August <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s latest in his series of plays about the black experience in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, each set in a different decade. His `` Fences,'' set in the 1950s, which won him a Pulitzer Prize last year, is still running. <PERSON> Lanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who won the 1980 Pulitzer Prize for `` Talley's Folly,'' one of his cycle of plays about the <PERSON> Talley </PERSON> family on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>, has a contender this season that is n't in that series, `` Burn This. Three possible `` best play'' nominees are based on real happenings. `` M. Butterfly'' is about a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> diplomat who had an affair with a <ORGANIZATION> Ch