ibed as <PERSON> Agca </PERSON>'s right arm and best friend. The prosecutor had asked for a life sentence for <PERSON> Celik </PERSON>, who was at large and tried in absentia on charges of firing at the pope with <PERSON> Agca </PERSON>. <PERSON> Celik </PERSON> was acquitted for lack of evidence. Under Italian law, acquittal for lack of evidence does not amount to a complete finding of innocence. It means that the court believes there is a possibility of guilt but that it did not hear enough evidence to support a conviction. Turkish officials were not immediately available to comment on the reports of his detention. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said it had no comment on the reports.
