<FIRST>u i AM-Denmark Bjt   05-08 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denmark, Bjt,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danes Asked To Choose: No-Nuke Policy or NATO Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> on Tuesday will be faced with the tricky choice between their <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies and their longstanding opposition to nuclear weapons in one of the country's most important elections since World War II. The sudden storm over <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s role in the 16-nation alliance came as a surprise to many voters, usually more worried about unemployment and national debt than military issues. A ban on nuclear weapons in peacetime has already been in effect for three decades. The showdown began April 14 when the opposition, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, pushed through a parliamentary resolution requiring the government to notify visiting warships of the nuclear arms ban. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> never confirm or deny the presence of nuclear weapons on their ships. The allies reacted sharply, saying the move jeopardized <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s participation in the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. A meeting of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s Nuclear Planning Group was rescheduled from <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> called off several <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> port visits. Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> supporter, called a general election, asking voters to `` take a stand'' on the issue. `` Has the <PERSON> Danes </PERSON>' national pride deteriorated so much that we will bow to pressure from abroad?'' the left-leaning newspaper Information asked in a front-page editorial. `` The question is the central one in the current debate, and in that sense, the election is the most important since the Second World War.'' It did n't help matters when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> joked to reporters that `` Danish means breakfast to me.'' National radio played the English-language tape on the air, an unusual step, and the liberal Politiken newspaper printed the sarcastic headline, `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> staff demonstrates its knowledge of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> later apologized. The confrontation comes at a politically unstable time for this country of 5.1 million. The last general election in September left <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s four-party coalition holding just 70 of the Folketing's 179 votes, but with enough support to command a majority on economic matters Tuesday's vote is not a direct referendum on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, but a vote for representatives in the Folketing. What happens afterward depends on how many votes are split among the Social Democrats, the biggest single party, <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s center-right coalition and a handful of smaller parties. Polls indicate that while most Danes agree with the traditional anti-nuclear position, many have contradictory feelings about <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. One survey said 82 percent of those asked favored a nuclear-free zone in <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, and 46 percent said they would support the idea even if it meant <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s expulsion from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. But a recent poll by the Observa organization showed that 66 percent of <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> favor staying in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and just 16 percent oppose membership, the most lopsided margin in years. Another published survey showed that 46 percent of <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> believed it was reasonable to ask <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> ships to guarantee they carry no nuclear arms, 36 percent did not and 18 percent were undecided. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s low-lying peninsula and islands command the approaches to the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> strategists envision it as a key supply point in case of a Soviet invasion. The NATO-Danish clash follows years of contention over <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s declining defense spending, which now amounts to 2.1 percent of its gross national product, among the lowest in the alliance But in random interviews with window shoppers along <PERSON> Stroeget </PERSON>, a pedestrian street in the heart of <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, voters seemed more worried about domestic matters than global politics. `` It's not just a question about nuclear weapons but about the way the government runs society,'' said <PERSON> Susane </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>, a conservative voter who works in a health insurance office. `` We have to face these economic problems.'' Unemployment is running at 9.7 percent. With a national debt worth more than $ 43 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has warned that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s currency could run into trouble unless costs are kept under control. <PERSON> Joergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Thy </PERSON>, editor and writer for a computer magazine, said he planned to vote against the government because `` I do n't think they have achieved much.'' The nuclear question? `` That's a joke. That's not the issue. Something went wrong in the corridors,'' he said. The no-nuclear notification letter _ the cause of the fuss _ has yet to be written. It's likely the note would simply restate national policy without requiring a response from the ships' commanders Defense setbacks are nothing new for the Danish government. The April 14 resolution was its 23rd loss in parliament since 1982 on a defense question. It passed by 75 to 58, with 46 lawmakers absent. But the timing of the resolution, as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> discuss further cutbacks in nuclear weapons, probably touched a nerve on the American side, speculated <PERSON> Nikolaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, a professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Aarhus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` When the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> reacts vigorously, it could therefore be linked to the fact that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> has contested an important American negotiating position,'' he wrote in Det Fri Aktuelt newspaper.
</TEXT>
