<FIRST>r i AM-Denmark-ElectionGlance     05-08 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denmark-Election Glance,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danish Election at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Denmark-Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are facts and figures on <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s general election called for Tuesday in a dispute over its nuclear arms policy in light of its membership in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ELIGIBLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 There are 3.9 million Danes over 18 who are eligible to vote, out of the country's population of 5.1 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AT STAKE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 All seats in the 179-member unicameral legislature, the Folketing, which sits for a maximum four-year term. A party must get at least 2 percent of the vote to win a seat. <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Faroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> are represented by two deputies each.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RUNNING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 There are 12 parties contesting the vote. _ The center-right governing coalition, now holding 70 seats, is comprised of the Conservative, <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and Chrstian People's parties. _ The opposition bloc controls 81 seats and includes the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>'s parties. _ The non-aligned parties are the nine-seat <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, an anti-tax group on the far right; the 11-seat Social-Liberals, which supports the government on domestic issues and votes with the opposition on foreign issues; and the maverick far-left <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Course </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 4 seats. The four members from <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Faroes </ORGANIZATION> split evenly between the oppostion and coalition. _ Also running are the environmentalist <ORGANIZATION> Danish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and the Leftwing Socialists. The leading candidates are Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, 59, of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, who has headed the government since 1982; <PERSON> Svend </PERSON> <PERSON> Auken </PERSON>, 45, named <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leader after the previous election; and <PERSON> Niels </PERSON> <PERSON> Helveg </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, 49, of the Social-Liberals, who could form a government in the event of an election stalemate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ISSUE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A resolution sponsored by the Social Democrats obliging <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to notify visiting warships that nuclear arms are barred from Danish ports in peacetime. The April 14 resolution, which passed 75-58, was sharply criticized by <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> as a challenge to its common nuclear strategy, and <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> called the election rather than carry out the motion. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> portrayed the vote as a choice between preserving or risking <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s full membership in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Auken </PERSON> said the government is exaggerating the defense issue, and wants to broaden the campaign to economic issues such as unemployment and welfare spending.
</TEXT>
