<FIRST>r i AM-Singapore     05-08 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Singapore,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singapore Defends Ouster Of U.S. Diplomat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Sunday defended its ouster of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat and offered to back up charges that he meddled in local politics. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> agreed with `` deep regret'' to a request from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> Saturday to withdraw <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON>, a political attache. The government also asked that <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> be reprimanded along with two unidentified senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials who it said sanctioned his activities. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gong </PERSON> denied allegations, made by the Home Affairs Ministry, that <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> interfered in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s politics. In meeting members of the political opposition, `` which appears to be the basis of the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> government's protest, Mr. <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> was doing what American diplomats are expected to do in any country, namely to keep in touch with a broad spectrum of individuals in order to report accurately developments in the country in question,'' <PERSON> Gong </PERSON> said. In a statement Sunday, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> said it would not `` capriciously or arbitrarily expel diplomats from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, especially when the diplomat in question represents a friendly nation.'' `` The assertion that <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> has not in any way acted improperly can only be a diplomatic fig leaf which the government is content to allow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to wear,'' the statement said. <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> contends that <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> met with opposition activists and urged them to contest upcoming elections. Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is heavily favored to retain control of this island republic of 2.6 million people in elections that must be held by December 1989. The party holds all but one of the 79 seats in parliament and there is no viable opposition capable of dislodging it. <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> `` was trying to manipulate and instigate Singaporeans, in order to bring about a particular political outcome,'' the government said. His explusion was an unprecedented jolt to normally warm relations between the two countries. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> long ago established close personal and political ties with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and recently returned from `` private'' talks with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the largest buyer of <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s exports and one of the biggest investors in this former British colony that gained full independence in 1965. The diplomatic tiff is the latest in a chain of events that began with the arrests last year of 22 Singaporeans accused of belonging to a `` clandestine communist network.'' They were seized under the Internal Security Act which allows for indefinate detention without trial. All but one were freed by Dec. 26, most of them with restrictions on their movements. Among them was a lawyer, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Seong </PERSON>, who allegedly was urged by <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> to fight the government. <PERSON> Seong </PERSON> was arrested again on April 19 along with eight of the 22 former detainees. That was less than 24 hours after the eight proclaimed their innocence and said they had been abused and coerced into making incriminating statements late last year. On April 28, the <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the eight had sworn fresh declarations withdrawing their allegations and reconfirming their original guilt. They are still behind bars and officials said an investigation continues. Besides <PERSON> Seong </PERSON>, 34, <PERSON> Hendrickson </PERSON> was linked by the government to lawyer <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Seow </PERSON>, 59. <PERSON> Seow </PERSON> was arrested Friday, hours after he appeared in court seeking the release of two of those arrested April 19. <PERSON> Seow </PERSON>, a former solictor-general and one time president of the <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, is being held without charge under the Internal Security Act `` for purposes of investigation into foreign interferences in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s internal affairs.'' Trade and Industry Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsien </PERSON> <PERSON> Loong </PERSON> said two distinct phases of the so-called political movement had become clear. One was a Marxist conspiracy involving the original 22, the other was separate action by foreign elements who made use of the detainees to meddle in domestic politics, he said.
