<FIRST>r w AM-Army-Bolts     05-08 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army-Bolts,490</SECOND>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dingell: Weak Bolts Causing `Serious Problems' in Two Army Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Army has `` serious problems'' in two of its front-line units because of continuing problems with weak bolts in some vehicles, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., said Sunday The problem may be even more extensive than that because the two units received their bolts from the same depots that supply other <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units, both here and overseas, said <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> also heads the investigations subcommittee, which held widely publicized hearings last August revealing problems of bolts and fasteners that were n't as strong as expected. The result is that wheel assemblies on some <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> vehicles, such as trucks and the all-purpose `` Hum-V,'' may come lose, according to testimony that will be presented Monday to the investigations subcommittee during a follow-up hearing. A subcommittee staff report said the problem fasteners were still found in large numbers in vehicles of the 7th Infantry division at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ord </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and the 9th Regiment at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tansill </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Material </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the depots that supply the bolts, admitted the service is still having problems `` We're very concerned about this,'' Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` We have been remiss in not educating soldiers at the lowest level about using the right grade of bolts.'' But she noted that in a series of tests, `` we've found that many of the bolts are still effective, even though they are substandard compared to contract specifications.'' The subcommittee staff report noted that `` the vehicles of the units we visited contained a number of fasteners from foreign manufacturers whose bolts had previously been found substandard in numerous laboratory tests.'' `` The combat units were experiencing severe fastener problems on their vehicles to the extent that the combat readiness of some units was affected,'' it said. Because the fasteners were not as strong as they should have been, some of them came lose in front wheel assemblies of the Hum-V, the investigators found. `` This caused tire wear, fastener failure, and if not corrected, loss of steering.'' In a check of the 9th Regiment, half of the 102 Hum-Vs checked had loose fasteners and seven had been lost from service because the problem was so severe, the subcommittee investigators found. One officer got so frustrated with trying to get the right fasteners that he `` bought replacement bolts from the civilian economy with money from his own pocket in order to get the unit's vehicles ready By a stroke of luck, he obtained domestic bolts at the local hardware store,'' the report said. Part of the problem is that bolts are stored in a variety of bins and the containers are n't always clearly marked, according to Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. The subcommittee investigators agreed, reporting that <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> maintenance personnel `` admitted that over 50 percent of their bins contained fasteners of unknown quality and complained that they were not receiving sufficient information to purge the suspect fasteners.''
