<HEAD>Wild ISU Weekend Prompts Festival Reappraisal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After sparking three consecutive nights of violence, <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s annual spring festival faces an overhaul in order to curb excessive drinking, school officials and student organizers of the festival agree. `` We're looking to work with the university and city to see what changes we can make,'' said <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, a sophomore from <LOCATION> Geneseo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, who is on the committee for the <LOCATION> Veishea </LOCATION> festival, an annual long weekend of student activities. Early Sunday, eight law officers were injured and 45 people were arrested as student celebrations coinciding with <PERSON> Veishea </PERSON> concluded. There were two arrests early Friday and nine early Saturday. `` This certainly mars what has been a very good weekend for Veishea. But we're going to have to reassess the whole Veishea activity ... and the amount of time students have off,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Thielen </PERSON>, university vice president of student affairs. He was on the scene early Sunday as raucous students set fires in streets and pelted officers and police vehicles with rocks and bottles. Student organizers of the 66th annual Veishea festival disavowed the rioting, saying it was not connected with any formal activities that included a parade on Saturday that was followed by the football team's spring game. occurred. The event was named by taking the first letter in the name of each of <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s original colleges `` We've been trying to promote the non-alcoholic aspect of <LOCATION> Veishea </LOCATION> this year,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said later Sunday. `` We do n't know why things got out of hand.'' Helmeted police clashed with an estimated crowd of 2,000 early Sunday in the heart of campus, where bonfires were fed by sofas and other furniture carried by beer-drinking revelers. Nightly disturbances at the annual spring festival started Thursday and grew progressively worse before the festival ended Sunday. Like the previous two nights, the latest disturbance appeared to start with private parties. `` It was pretty ugly for a while,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballantine </PERSON>. `` Frankly, I have n't seen anything like this since the early 1970s and the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war protests. `` The only difference is those people had a legitimate gripe. These people did n't. They were just drunk.'' As state, county and city law enforcement officers helped firefighters move in to put out the fires Sunday, they were pelted with bottles and rocks thrown by crowd members. Two police cars were damaged when hit by concrete blocks. At least two people in the crowd were burned, but not seriously, said police dispatcher <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. When law officers had little success persuading the crowd to disperse, the school's popular basketball coach, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, came to campus after 3 a.m. and pleaded with students to go home. <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> warned them their actions were damaging the school's reputation. The crowd broke up a short time later. Most of the 45 people arrested were charged with inciting to riot, an aggravated misdemeanor. Eight officers were treated and released at <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greeley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, with two requiring stitches to close wounds. The violence erupted as dozens of officers from the Ames police department, the Story County sheriff's department, the state patrol and campus security lined both sides of <LOCATION> Welch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, a strip of taverns and small shops, esc