<HEAD>Saudi-Iran Split Mirrors Age-Old Moslem Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 13-14 ``The Sunnis ...'' with 2 grafs to ADD Sunni
belief on heirs to faith.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The animosity between <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that has led to their recent diplomatic split is rooted in a centuries-old schism in the Moslem world between the Sunni and <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> sects. <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 Islamic revolution in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which is predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION>, dragged the religious feud into the 20th century, sparking new fears among the conservative, Sunni-dominated <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> states and other Arab countries. The revolution's triumph in toppling the pro-Western <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON> also fueled Islamic fervor among fundamentalist Sunnis. That, along with the vigorous <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> challenge, has ignited violence from socialist <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> to monarchist <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> in the last decade. The Islamic resurgence has brought a religious intensity not witnessed since the Middle Ages and has perplexed and alarmed the West. While the <LOCATION> Saudis </LOCATION> cited terrorism and threats for breaking relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> on April 27, they mainly were seeking to head off Iranian-inspired violence in the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> in this year's annual haj, or pilgrimage. More than 400 pilgrims, 275 of them Iranians, were killed in rioting in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> last year that shocked the Moslem world. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> vowed revenge and <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> called for the overthrow of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s royal family. The Saudis want to avoid a repetition of the violence this year by getting Moslem countries to scale down the number of pilgrims they send. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, asked to trim its contingent of the usual 150,000 by about one-third, refuses. Instead, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has revived calls for an Islamic crusade against <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and stripping the royal family of custodianship of Islam's holiest shrines in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, Prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s birthplace, and in <LOCATION> Medina </LOCATION>, where he is buried. The guardianship of these holy sites is one of the underpinnings of the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> monarchy that gives it political legitimacy in the eyes of most Moslems. The deepening hostility between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has been exacerbated by the 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war, in which the Saudis have supported <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> The Arabs and Persians, separated by language and culture, have been religious rivals since the death of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, the founder of <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>, in 632 A.D. The Sunnis, who make up more than 90 percent of the world's 850 million Moslems, revere <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> as second only to God and view <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakr </PERSON>, the prophet's father-in-law and the man who became Islam's first caliph, as his rightful successor The mystical Shiites consider <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s cousin and son-in-law, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, the fourth caliph, and 11 of his descendants to be the true heirs of the faith. They revere all 12 as imams, or saints, and believe the 12th imam, <PERSON> Mehdi </PERSON>, will return like a messiah to bring justice to the world. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> was assassinated in 661 amid a power struggle by two factions over who would lead the Moslem world following <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s death <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s death confirmed the Sunni Umayyad dynasty in power as the Caliphs, or successors of the prophet. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s descendants remained in perpetual revolt, claiming to be the true Caliphate and refusing to accept orthodox teachings espoused by the Sunnis. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, led one rebellion and was massacred with his handful of outnumbered followers in the Battle of <LOCATION> Karbala </LOCATION>, in what is now <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, in 680. Ever since, the minority Shiites were considered heretics. Only in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, where for political motives a 16th century shah embraced <PERSON> Shiitism </PERSON> as the established creed, did the downtrodden sect flourish. Every year, when they mark the death of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, militant Shiites flagellate themselves with chains and swords in a passionate celebration of the martyr _ acts which Sunnis regard as demeaning. For <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> and his followers, their revolution was the dawn of a new age of Islamic fundamentalism as a powerful force in the world, the time of reckoning after 1,300 years of subjugation. The revival stems in part from Moslems rebelling against the Western influence that colonialism brought and oil wealth intensified in the last two decades, transforming what were feudal societies and eroding cultural values. In this vacuum, fundamentalism has taken root. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s belief that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is the beacon for a fundamentalist revival that will sweep the world and his drive to export the revolution has caused mayhem among the monarchies of the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> who believe themselves vulnerable. The Iran-Iraq war has only heightened the passions. Tiny <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, which is closest to the war zone and under constant threat from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, has cracked down hard on its <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> militants after a chain of terrorist attacks, including the April 5 hijacking of a Kuwaiti jetliner by <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> extremists. On Sunday, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> al-Anbaa </ORGANIZATION> called for the government to deport Shiite Moslems who show allegiance to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Shiites comprise about one-fourth of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s 1.9 million population. In <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, where Sunnis rule, the Shiites form about 70 percent of the population. Seven years ago, <LOCATION> Bahraini </LOCATION> authorities foiled what apparently was a Shiite plot aimed at assassinating the ruler, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> <PERSON> bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sulman </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Khalifa </PERSON>. Fundamentalism inspired by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s revolution has reared up further afield. <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> broke off relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> last year, alleging <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was seeking to foster an Islamic rebellion. Fundamentalists assassinated President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1980 and remain politically active there. Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> crushed a rebellion by the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> in the city of <LOCATION> Hama </LOCATION> in 1982, slaughtering as many as 30,000 people and razing much of the city. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s decision to sever relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> has increased the polarization between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> zealots and the <LOCATION> Arabs </LOCATION> that the Iran-Iraq war has brought. But the Saudis also were throwing down the gauntlet to their <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> rivals only a few weeks before the haj is due to start, and that could have dangerous consequences in their feud.
