<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Polish official, responding to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration criticism of a crackdown on labor unrest, denied Sunday that strikers were beaten and said a government that fired its air traffic controllers should know the difference between a legal and an illegal strike. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Wieslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON>, Polish government political adviser, denied news reports and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government allegations of violence against striking workers at a <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> steel mill and accused the news media of exaggerating and inflaming conditions in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` The strike was crushed, but nobody was beaten,'' <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said in an interview from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Week with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>.'' `` If it all were true what your news media is reporting, we would have a general strike, a nationwide strike of 10 days or perhaps three months,'' <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said. At least five strikes have occurred in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in the past two weeks, including one at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard where negotiations were continuing between workers and management. Asked about the reported use of percussion grenades to quell the <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> strike, which had lasted 10 days, <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said he did not believe the devices were used but added, `` I can not rule it out.'' Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> condemned the reported violence Saturday and announced that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> backing for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s economic recovery program would remain frozen until the program wins popular support. The White House twice last week also issued statements condemning the government's reported use of force against strikes backed by the outlawed Solidarity labor movement. <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> did not directly respond to the official <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> criticism. But he said, `` You know, a country which not long ago had a certain experience with its air traffic controllers union ... should make a clear-cut difference between a strike which is legal ... and wildcat strikes, which as you know very well are illegal.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> fired striking air traffic controllers after what the government said was an illegal strike in 1981. <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said strikes represent problems with adaptation to `` the new style of our economic life.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, including Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during a visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> last September, had applauded Polish steps toward economic reform prior to the current unrest. In March, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, was posted in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> for the first time in five years.
