detained. PICKS up 11th graf, `Many dissident ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet police on Sunday tried to interrupt meetings of scores of dissidents seeking to challenge the supremacy of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and detained 20 people as they left one of the gatherings, dissidents said. Editors of 30 non-official journals hoping to break the government monopoly on publishing also met in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to formalize their cooperation by establishing the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. On Saturday, 148 people attended an initial meeting to form an alternative political party called the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. On Sunday, they broke into groups to discuss the party's political platform and socio-economic and organizational questions. <PERSON> Yevgeniya </PERSON> <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON>, who hosted the meeting about the group's political platform, said police arrived at her north <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment in about 30 cars Sunday evening and tried to enter About 50 people were jammed in Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON>'s living room, thrashing out the group's political goals. Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON> said the group refused to let officers in, but 20 people were detained as they left. She said in a telephone interview that she did not know what happened to them, but noted that authorities often hold people for several hours and then release them. Smaller groups discussed the party's organization and socio-economic policies at two other <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartments. <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsarkov </PERSON>, leader of the organizational meeting, said a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> city official accompanied by police arrived at the meeting and asked that the group of 15 disband. Police asked to check their documents, but the participants refused and police eventually left, <PERSON> Tsarkov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliseyedko </PERSON>, head of the group on socio-economic problems, said police also visited that meeting and checked documents, but otherwise did not interfere. Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON> said in an interview earlier Sunday that a committee of 15 people had drafted political principles calling for: _ Multi-party, parliamentary democracy; _ A new constitution, replacing the current document that makes the Communist Party the `` leading and guiding force'' of Soviet society; _ Independent trade unions; and _ Withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from Eastern European countries and from the western <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> and the Baltic states, which Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON> said the group considers to be under Soviet occupation. The meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and the independent publishers group were were notable for the number of people they drew to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Authorities have not broken up previous efforts to hold dissident conferences, but they have closed conference facilities and prevented some people from traveling to them. Many dissident groups and independent publications have sprung up since hundreds of political prisoners were freed in 1987. Authorities in the past have crushed efforts to form an opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and despite his reform effort, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has given no indication the party will tolerate any opposition. Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will allow the group to exist if he is serious about reforms. `` Arguments and disagreements are normal in society,'' she said. But any such group also faces enormous difficulties in a vast country where the government controls printing facilities and authorities can detain or intimidate dissidents and disrupt mail and telephone calls. On Saturday, dissident sources said police surrounded the apartment building across the street from the government offices of the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> republic, where the first meeting was held, but did not break it up. Ms. <PERSON> Debryanskaya </PERSON> said her group will make a formal declaration seeking official recognition of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and transmit it to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> city authorities. She has been active in a group supporting greater trust between East and West, and a second group calling itself `` Democracy and Humanism.'' Former political prisoners <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Timofeyev </PERSON>, and other publishers of independent journals from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lvov </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pskov </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Kuybyshev </PERSON> decided at their weekend gatherings to form a library to preserve and help disseminate their publications. Thirty publications emphasizing such topics as political commentary, religion and women's issues were represented, participants said. A similar meeting was held in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> last fall, and the group agreed to hold another large conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in October. Some of the publications have sought official approval, but none has been given. Participants in the editors' gathering said police checked documents of people who arrived at the south <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment on Saturday, but no police or plainclothes officers were visible Sunday.
