<HEAD>Civil Libertarian Says Coast Guard Drug Policy Unfair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The weekend seizure of a $ 2.5 million yacht after less than one-tenth of an ounce of marijuana was found on board is a headline-grabbing scare tactic that violates common sense, a civil libertarian said Sunday. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s seizure of boats like the 133-foot Ark Royal was meant to make an impact. `` This new policy should be taken as fair warning to anyone who is using or transporting any detectable amount of drugs on our waterways,'' <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said when he announced the `` Zero Tolerance'' policy here two weeks ago. But <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Coombs </PERSON>, a member of the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the policy sets a dangerous precedent. `` To take somebody's property from them for something they probably could n't control'' is excessive, she said Sunday. The Ark Royal, registered in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and operated only by a crew of six employees, was boarded Saturday in international waters in the <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Neither its registered owner, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogerson </PERSON>, described by the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> as the president and chief shareholder of <ORGANIZATION> Tomima </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, nor any passengers were on board, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Felker </PERSON>. A boarding party from the cutter <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> noticed a tiny bit of marijuana residue in a trash can during a friendly document check. The resulting search revealed a little marijuana tucked in the dresser of a stateroom, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said. `` At this point the person who owned the contraband has not come forward,'' <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> said. The crew will probably be released uncharged when they arrive at the <ORGANIZATION> Key </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> station, expected during the night, he said. The yacht was to be impounded. `` We have been focusing all of our efforts in recent years on just the big smugglers, but drugs are a two-way street,'' <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said. `` This is the time we're making the users pay. It really has to hurt to see a luxury yacht taken away for what basically amounts to one joint.'' Asked if it did n't seem harsh to take away the boat under those circumstances, <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> said, `` Zero tolerance means exactly that, without regards to the size of the vessel or of value of the vessel.'' `` A U.S.-flagged vessel is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory anywhere in the world. We have authority to enforce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> laws over that vessel anywhere in the world except in the territorial seas of a foreign state. Even then we may be granted authority by that foreign state,'' <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is stretching the law with its seizure policy, said Ms. <PERSON> Coombs </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may have passed a law that permits confiscation of property used in drug trafficking, but `` that's not the same as saying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had in mind that they would have a Zero Tolerance policy,'' she said. It violates a sense of `` proportionality,'' Ms. <PERSON> Coombs </PERSON> said. `` It's putting people at enormous risk with no very effective way of protecting themselves, and as a civil libertarian I am troubled by that kind of policy.'' `` My guess is the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> is going to fight pretty hard on this one,'' she said. `` It's going to have enormous symbolic value.'' The previously most-expensive vessel confiscated under the program was a $ 300,000 yacht seized off <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>. Efforts to reach <PERSON> Rogerson </PERSON> for comment Sunday were unsuccessful. There was no listing under that name in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. There was a person with that name in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, but he had an unlisted number. Efforts to find a listing for a <ORGANIZATION> Tomima </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> were also unsuccessful.
