<HEAD>Irish Prison Guards Vote to End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prison guards voted by a huge majority Sunday to end their first national strike after three weeks. The 1,900 guards struck April 15 in a dispute over scheduling. The government used 1,000 police officers and 300 soldiers as temporary guards. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the guards voted 1,140-159 to accept an offer for an independent review of new shift arrangements. Irish Justice Minister <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> welcomed Sunday's vote and said talks would be held with guards Monday to arrange a return to work. The union had said the shifts were imposed without consultation. It also said it wanted government money earmarked for overtime to be used instead to recruit more prison staff. But the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> said the dispute centered on a demand by guards for compensation for overtime payments they lost last year when extra prison staff was recruited. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s 11 prisons house about 2,000 inmates.
