<HEAD>Banks To Allow Limited Withdrawals For First Time in Nine Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Under government pressure, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s banks prepared to allow customers to make limited withdrawals from their accounts Monday for the first time in more than nine weeks A government order shut down banks on March 3 following a run on savings by panicky depositors and the imposition of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions in an effort to force Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to resign as commander of the Defense Forces. The sanctions, including the freezing of an estimated $ 50 million of government funds in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> accounts, helped produce a severe cash shortage in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, which uses the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar as its currency. After rejecting earlier government orders to resume operations with restrictions, some financial institutions agreed to reopen on April 18 to accept deposits. A week later, the government allowed them to expand transactions, but cash withdrawals were still barred. Meanwhile, the government refused to allow <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Rogelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> to re-enter the country. He had recently arranged bail for some members of the opposition National Civic Crusade. <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Marcela </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, said her husband was put on a plane leaving <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> when he tried to return Saturday from <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. She said <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> was taken to a security office and told `` absolutely nothing'' before he was expelled. Some Civic Crusade leaders have been hiding for weeks after security forces raided their offices and homes. Several opposition leaders have been refused re-entry or expelled during the 11-month-long political crisis and then allowed to return later. Panamanians, unable to cash their paychecks, have conducted business on a barter or cash-only basis since the closing of the banks. Public employees have received government checks in small denominations which they can use to buy groceries or pay utility bills. Supermarkets that take the checks use them to pay utility bills and taxes. Bankers and government officials agreed after a series of negotiations to resume limited withdrawals beginning Monday. Some bankers said the compromise was little more than an attempt to produce the image of business as usual since the cash crisis has not eased. The banks `` will be open, but they will not be open,'' said <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Felliu </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Industrialists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Rules issued by the government's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> limit the amount Panamanians will be able to withdraw from checking accounts to 25 percent of the balance on March 3 with a maximum of $ 10,000. Money deposited after April 18 is to be free of restrictions. Withdrawals from savings accounts are to be limited to $ 50, beginning a month after the reopening. Withdrawals of interest are unrestricted. All withdrawals are subject to the availability of cash at the individual bank. The government's <ORGANIZATION> Caja </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahorro </ORGANIZATION> bank announced it would not cash checks for the time being. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION>, which normally honors government checks, also said it would not pay out cash. The <ORGANIZATION> Panamana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 93 of the 117 banks, most of them foreign, previously insisted its members would not resume full services unless the government could assure an adequate supply of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars to back normal customer and commercial transactions. Some bankers said they would abide by the agreement but insisted that conditions still did not exist for full-service operations. `` If that is their thinking, they are part of the aggression against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> said on Friday. Two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> indicted the general in February on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has denied the charges and said they are politically motivated. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s crisis worsened after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who controls the civilian government, had the legislature depose President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> on Feb. 26, the day after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire the general as commander of the 15,000-member Defense Forces. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still recognizes <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as president and imposed the sanctions.
