<HEAD>Man Accused in 16 Slayings to Be Tried Monday for Two of Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man accused in 16 deaths, including the Christmastime slaughter of 14 relatives, will go to trial first for the two killings outside his family. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, 47, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> master sergeant, is charged with two counts of capital murder in the Dec. 28 shooting spree in <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION> in which six people were shot by a gunman wielding two .22 caliber pistols. Two of the victims died. In his trial, which begins Monday, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> could be sentenced to die or to life in prison without parole if convicted of either count of capital murder. He also will be tried on five counts of attempted capital murder and one of kidnapping. The defense will ask Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> to dismiss the attempted capital murder counts on grounds that, under <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> law, they are superseded by the capital murder counts, according to defense attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. Following the shooting spree, 14 members of <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> family were found slaughtered. Charges from the slaying of the family are to be tried later. The 16 deaths made it one of the worst mass slayings in American history. The case was moved to <LOCATION> Ozark </LOCATION> after the defense argued that there had been so much pretrial publicity that it would be difficult to get an unprejudiced jury in <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION>, 47 miles west of here. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> declined to say whether <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> would testify. The attorney said Sunday that he had no plans `` at this time'' to raise insanity as a defense. Tests on <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> found no evidence of a problem such as a brain tumor that could have affected his behavior. After his arrest, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> was was found by doctors to be legally sane and thus able to stand trial. Moments before he surrendered Dec. 28, police said, the gunman told his hostage: `` I've gotten everybody who wanted to hurt me. I've come to do what I wanted to do. It's all over now.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> will be on trial for the deaths of <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, 24, who police say once spurned <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' romantic advances, and of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>, 33, who police say was a chance victim. Miss <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> was shot in the head at a <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION> law office where she was a legal secretary. <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON> was slain at an oil company where the gunman wounded the oil company owner. To be tried later are two capital murder charges, one accusing <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> of killing seven relatives, the other accusing him of killing seven other relatives. There are two groups of seven because authorities believe the killings took place at different times. After <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> was arrested, sheriff's deputies found the bodies of five relatives, including two of his children and their spouses. Four of the victims had been shot and the other victim, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' 11-year-old granddaughter, had been strangled They apparently died after they arrived for a Christmas season family gathering, police said. The next day, police dug into a shallow, kerosene-soaked grave and found seven bodies, including those of <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' other children and his wife, <PERSON> Becky </PERSON>. She had told family members in a letter `` I am a prisoner here, and the kids, too.'' Police said that some of these victims had been shot, others strangled, apparently before Christmas _ gift packages were unopened beneath the Christmas tree. Police also found the bodies of two infant boys in garbage sacks in the trunks of abandoned cars on <PERSON