<FIRST>r p AM-Politics-Optimism     05-08 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Politics-Optimism,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Tend To Vote For The Optimistic Candidate, Researchers
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In nine of the past 10 presidential elections, the candidate who avoided discussing problems and offered an optimistic outlook was the winner, according to researchers. They say those results are being borne out this year, because, of the pack of presidential hopefuls who began the race, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and apparent <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> offered the rosiest messages. In analyzing nomination acceptance speeches of the two major-party candidates since 1948, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Seligman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON>, psychologists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, found the candidate who avoided dwelling on national and personal problems and characterized troubles with an optimistic outlook ended up in the White House _ except in 1968. That year, <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, whose message rated slightly more upbeat than <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s, came from behind in the polls to a narrow defeat on Election Day, <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON> said. `` The danger is it tells a political candidate that if you shape statements to what they want to hear _ you'll win. ... An unscrupulous candidate can move further away from what he really means,'' <PERSON> Seligman </PERSON> said. The correlation between the candidates' ratings in the analysis and their actual margins of victory or defeat came almost as close as is possible in social science, <PERSON> Seligman </PERSON> said. The researchers applied their theory to the 13 major candidates running at the beginning of the year for the Democratic and Republican nominations by analyzing texts of their speeches as published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in January and February. The results of the study are due for publication in The American Psychologist, a psychology journal, later this year. The researchers counted the number of references to bad events or problems, then had people who were unaware of the source of the sentences rate them for pessimism and optimism. On the Democratic side, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> came in as the optimism winner, followed by Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was the winner for the Republicans, with former <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> behind him. Key to the high ratings for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON> said, was the low number of references to bad events. But also a major factor in the equation was their tendency to view the problems optimistically, citing forces outside the country or painting them as temporary troubles that would be overcome by a vote in their favor, he said. While <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign has been punctuated by a theme of hope, his speeches frequently have focused on the problems of American society and politics, <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> tends to shy away more from discussing the country's problems, he said For instance, a passage from a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> speech about defense has him firmly blaming the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration but using strong language in describing perceived troubles, <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said: `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> put out the deal that we are weak militarily. That's not true. We're the strongest military in the world.'' But, he adds: `` Our boys got killed in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> ... Our boys are vulnerable in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, going up and down that river every day being looked at down the gun barrel of American made guns sold to the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> illegally. We've got a strong military and a weak commander in chief.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> loses points in the analysis by rekindling the trauma of the 241 Marines and sailors killed by a car bomb in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the current threat to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, scored higher than the other party candidates by not dwelling on a problem and quickly looking to an optimistic future. `` Modern American voters seem to have a stable preference for candidates who are more hopeful,'' <PERSON> Zullow </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
