d be clued in to what's going on.'' `` This started out as something noble, something we've tried to have done for three years,'' said <PERSON> Ottinger </PERSON>. `` We are very, very sorry it happened this way. It was n't meant to turn out like this.'' The trustees decided in January that <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> should get the honorary degree. Students set up a committee to contact <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s family to get their approval University spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said letters were sent to <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, and his two daughters: <PERSON> Zenani </PERSON>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Makaziwe </PERSON>, a student at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. However, Northeastern still has not received approval from the <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> family, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> reported.
