<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The best of the worst, the tops of the lowest, the most awful assaults on the art of writing were honored Sunday in the annual Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest. The top prize, the `` creme de la dreck,'' went to <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheeley </PERSON>, 20, a journalism student at <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. `` I'd hate to say that bad writing comes naturally, but my creative juices were flowing that day,'' <PERSON> Sheeley </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Sunday. `` You have to get into a bad frame of mind.'' She said she is a would-be novelist, `` But I'm a pretty bad procrastinator, so for now I want to go into newspaper writing and have a deadline to write for.'' Whether a boon or bane for her career, the prize came from <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, founder and `` grand panjandrum'' of the literary disgrace he calls `` the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> of literature.'' Despite the humor that surrounds its awarding, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> stresses that the competition is not a `` joke-writing contest. It really takes a very good writer to deliberately write bad.'' The contest trashes the battered memory of 19th century English writer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulwer-Lytton </PERSON>. His turgid style is captured in the opening line to one of his novels, later enshrined by <PERSON> Snoopy </PERSON>, the erudite pooch in the comic strip Peanuts: `` It was a dark and stormy night ...'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> notes that <PERSON> Bulwer-Lytton </PERSON> also is remembered for such ringing cliches as `` The pen is mightier than the sword'' and `` The Great Unwashed.'' This year's <ORGANIZATION> No-Ribbon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Undistinguished </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judges </ORGANIZATION> examined more than 11,000 entries, searching for the most miserable, least readable and rottenest lead sentence to the crummiest novel imaginable. This awful thing submitted by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheeley </PERSON> brought her to the top _ or the bottom _ of the heap: `` Like an expensive sports car, fine-tuned and well-built, <PERSON> Portia </PERSON> was sleek, shapely and gorgeous, her red jumpsuit moulding her body, which was as warm as the seatcovers in July, her hair as dark as new tires, her eyes flashing like bright hubcaps, and her lips dewy as the beads of fresh rain on the hood; she was a woman driven _ fueled by a single accelerant _ and she needed a man, a man who would n't shift from his views, a man to steer her along the right road: a man like <PERSON> Alf </PERSON> <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said the contest is a gentle reminder to the world of letters that it is OK to lighten up, forget the grammar books for a minute and have some fun, to `` approach the language recreationally as well as practically.'' For her effort, <ORGANIZATION> Sheeley </ORGANIZATION> wins a word processor. Awards were also made in selected categories. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>, won in puns: `` Once a month, when the moon is full, Reverend <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bleaker </PERSON> and his lovely wife <PERSON> Teddi </PERSON> invite members of the church to the parsonage for an evening of hymn singing, followed by cookies, tea, and a frenzied orgy on the lawn outside, making sure, of course, to take all the usual precautions for safe sects.'' <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazulelwicz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, won for purple prose: `` The silent snow fell relentlessly, unceasingly, mercilessly from the sordid, sullied surreality of the sky as if some enormous, ethereal diner were shaking grated parmesan on the great, soggy meatball that was earth.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stratford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, won for science fiction: `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> doubted that her alien escort, composed as he was of vegetable matter, seaweed, and a thick coating of swampy muck, would be a suitable date for the Intergalactic kegger, but he turned out to be a real FUNGI.'' <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Nottinghamshire </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, won for detective novel: `` With the radio squawking that a 4711 was in progress at 37th and 127th, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> knocked car 495 into 3rd and headed up 5th at 70, little reckoning, as he thumbed his .38, that this would be the day when his number came up.''
