<HEAD>Big Drop Predicted In U.S. Makers' Share of Auto Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car companies will see their share of the domestic auto market fall sharply in the next two years as Japanese companies increase their production here, a study has concluded. The management consulting firm of <PERSON> Booz </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Allen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> predicted that domestic companies' share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto market would fall to 56 percent in 1990 from 68 percent last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s auto makers should hold more than 30 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market by 1990, the newspaper quoted the study as forecasting. The firm's industry analysts estimated Japanese-based companies would be building about 2.2 million cars a year in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants by 1990, the newspaper said. That equals the number of cars that the Japanese export to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> annually under current voluntary restraints. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> build cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and three more Japanese companies plan to start production here by 1990. As a result of the competition, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors