<HEAD>With AM-Regan's Record Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> heiress who has authored books on astrology, said Sunday she is the `` friend'' who advised first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on matters such as safe times for the president to travel. `` I ca n't deny that she has consulted me,'' Ms. <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from her <LOCATION> Nob </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> home. `` I am very uncomfortable, however, with the situation because normally I never discuss the identity of my clients, and I never discuss their affairs.'' `` I am a serious, scientific astrologer and I am really not one of these clowns, and I really do n't like this circus atmosphere,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, who has been practicing astrology since 1960 and has written three books on the subject. Ms. <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>'s revelation followed reports on the book, `` For the Record; From Wall Street to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' in which <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> writes that `` virtually every major move and decision the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> made during my time as White House chief of staff was cleared in advance with a woman in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> who drew up horoscopes to make certain that the planets were in a favorable alignment for the enterprise.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> confessed that he never learned the identity of the woman, whom he said Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> referred to only as `` my friend in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.'' Time magazine, which published excerpts from the book, first identified the woman. Ms. <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, who frequently appears on the <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> television show, said she was first introduced to Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan <