<SECOND>AM-Japan Quake,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Rocks Northern Japan, No Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An earthquake hit <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s northernmost main island of Hokkaido Monday morning. Police said they had no reports of damage or casualties. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meteorological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the quake registered 5.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale and struck at 7:44 a.m. _ 6:44 p.m. Sunday EDT. It said the quake was centered in Hokkaido's <PERSON> Hidaka </PERSON> mountain range. Monday's tremor followed a strong earthquake that measured 6.4 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> and rocked Hokkaido Saturday. In that quake, which was centered off the coast of the island, local trains were temporarily halted while tracks were inspected but there was no serious damage. There have been two major earthquakes in Hokkaido in the past 35 years. A quake in 1968 killed 52 people. The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake registering 5 can cause considerable damage and one of six is capable of causing severe damage. A reading of 7 indicates a major quake. Each increase of one number represents a tenfold increase in magnitude.
