<HEAD>Finger-Pointing Over Bank Lending Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reports that many of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s banks restrict home loans in black neighborhoods have generated strong protests from political leaders despite bankers' denials. In a series of reports last week, The <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and The Atlanta Constitution said a study showed that white neighborhoods received five times as much money in home loans in 1986 as black neighborhoods with the same income level. The newspapers suggested that race helped determine lending patterns, an illegal practice known as red-lining. `` I want to hear from some of our banking friends and people at the savings and loans,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrington </PERSON>, who is black. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> formed a committee of bankers, politicians and citizens to investigate lending practices and make recommendations in 20 days. State banking commissioner <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> needs a law requiring banks to reinvest deposits in their communities. The <ORGANIZATION> Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> unanimously approved a law prohibiting discrimination in the sale, rental or finance of housing. `` I feel that the banks really do owe not only affirmative action in regard to this, but an apology to the city as a whole, whether they've known about it or not,'' said commission Chairman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>, who is black. `` And I think they owe us an apology for some of the characterizations they've made of the black community.'' The newspapers said federal statistics showed that loans to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s middle-income black neighborhoods averaged $ 339.27 per single-family home in 1986, compared with $ 2,432.82 in middle-income white neighborhoods. The newspapers also said banks closed branches or restricted business hours and gave lower property assessments in mostly black neighborhoods. They said the banking practices hindered economic development in the city's mostly black south side. Officials of several financial institutions that attended a special <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meeting last week denied that anything other than economics determines their lending. They did not dispute the newspapers' figures, though, and offered few suggestions for boosting loans in black areas. `` It's called the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rule </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> and Loan. `` Do n't lend money if you wo n't get it back.'' `` Much of the housing in predominately black areas is substandard, requiring rehabilitation to qualify for mortgage lending,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. `` As a result, this can not be handled through conventional mortgage lending channels.'' <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, a black-owned institution, disagreed. `` I have difficulty believing that most of the housing in black neighborhoods is substandard,'' he said. `` That is where the black community of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> really got its name nationally. People who come from outside are amazed: ` Black folks got these kinds of houses here?''' Citizens Trust, which lends mostly to blacks, had a lower default rate on real estate loans than the six largest banks in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and the lowest of any bank its size in the nation in 1986, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examination </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a government agency that reports for bank examiners. Some people suggested blacks should withdraw deposits from banks that wo n't do business with them. `` If lending policies and practices do not change substantially to meet the concerns and demands of the black consumer market, then withdrawing funds from the recalcitrant banks and banks with poor policies would be a logical step to take,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinhoster </PERSON>, Southeastern regional director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People.
