<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 1,000 supporters gathered at the hillside estate of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> on Sunday for a three-hour memorial service for the exiled <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> president's mother. `` A <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> that is free, democratic and strong, that is the legacy of my mother,'' <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> said in the eulogy. `` I shall not see her dead. I shall see her alive. She will be with me every day of my life,'' said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who was denied permission to return to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> for the funeral of <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON>, who died there Wednesday. <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, in a radio broadcast in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> on Sunday, reiterated that she decided against allowing <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return for security reasons. The Roman Catholic service here, which included recitation of the burial rites, was held on the lawn of the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> home. A small white tent was erected for the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> family and their close friends. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, and the couple's daughter, <PERSON> Irene </PERSON>, both sang, and several leaders of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> support groups spoke. Following the service the supporters who were transported to the estate on tour buses were fed McDonald's hamburgers, spaghetti and traditional Filipino foods. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his family have lived here since fleeing <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> in February 1986 during a largely non-violent uprising that brought Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to power.
