<HEAD>Ecuador Picks Successor to Pro-U.S. President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Borja thanking voters.
Pickup 2nd graf pvs ``Borja's rival...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> won Sunday's presidential election in the runoff race between two leftists to succeed pro-American President <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>. `` Thank you, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, thank you,'' <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> said on television in the capital. `` We will have a government by the people and for the people.'' Thousands of <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>'s supporters in <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION>, his highland stronghold, swarmed into the streets to celebrate and caravans of cars with their horns blaring packed the city's avenues. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>'s rival, <PERSON> Abdala </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, conceded defeat in an address over national television from his power base in <LOCATION> Guayaquil </LOCATION>. `` There are no excuses. Dr. <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> is the president of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> said. With the count nearly complete, <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> had 1,584,483 of the valid votes and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> 1,344,200. Political analysts had said the election was too close to call. Public opinion polls showed 25 percent of the country's 4.7 million eligible voters still undecided in the final weeks of the campaign. Election oficials had estimated the voter turnout would be about 80 percent. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> had conducted a bitter campaign marked by exchanges of insults in their race to replace <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, a conservative who has promoted free-market policies and befriended the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> voted in <LOCATION> Guayaquil </LOCATION> and discounted persistent rumors of a military coup if <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> is elected. Coups `` are out of fashion,'' he said. <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> has charged that the right spread the rumors to try to prevent him from winning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The election pitted <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, a 52-year-old law professor and leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, against <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, a tough-talking 36-year-old populist who vowed to `` punish the oligarchy.'' Sirens and church bells echoed Sunday through the streets of this city 9,300 feet high in the Andes, signaling opening of polls. Voters included colorfully dressed Highland Indians from the outskirts of the capital. Indians make up 35 percent of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s population of 10 million Campaign violence intensified in the final weeks before the election, leaving three people dead and more than a dozen wounded. Newspapers and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> leaders blamed the clashes on the vitriolic rhetoric of the candidates. <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Roldosista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, called his adversary a drunkard, a drug addict and an atheist, a potentially damaging accusation in this heavily Catholic nation. He also used coarse street language to question <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>'s manliness. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, an urbane, usually reserved politician from <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION>, responded with insults of his own, calling <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> a `` fascist ignoramus.'' <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> qualified for the runoff by leading a field of 10 candidates in the first round of voting Jan. 31. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> won 20 percent of the vote, and <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> took 15. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, came in third, a sign of his government's low popularity. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, who lost a close runoff to the president in 1984 and was making his third bid for the presidency, pledged to reverse the government's free-market economic policies and seek close ties to the non-aligned movement. <PERSON> Bucaram </PERSON> is political boss of the huge slums that sprawl over the outskirts of <LOCATION> Guayaquil </LOCATION>, the country's largest city and its major port. His opponents accused him of making demagogic appeals to the poor, including promises to give free shoes to all poor children and nearly double the monthly minimum wage to $ 55. His followers affectionally call him `` the crazy one'' because of his fiery speaking style. During the campaign, he recorded a song titled `` That's Why They Call Me Crazy.'' This small nation returned to democracy in 1979 after nine years of civilian and military dictatorships. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, whose four-year term ends in August, has had a stormy relationship with leftist and populist parties that controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He also put down a rebellion by an air force commander halfway through his presidency. His successor faces the most serious national economic crisis since <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> began exporting oil in the early 1970s. The economy shrank in 1987 by 3.5 percent, and inflation is expected to climb to at least 50 percent this year, the highest level since 1983. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>'s supporters blame the problems on a sharp drop in the price of oil, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s main source of income, and economic damage from a devastating earthquake in March 1987.
