<FIRST>d f PM-LightBeer     05-08 0925</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Light Beer,0958</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewers Look to Light Beers for Growth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 These are heady days for light beer. While overall growth in the beer business has flattened out, light beer sales remain effervescent. They have nearly doubled in the past seven years and now account for more than 24 percent of the overall beer market. The major brewers are encouraging the growth by spending nearly $ 220 million a year on advertising light beers, about a third of their total ad budgets, according to Leading National Advertisers, which tracks such spending. In the latest indication of the importance brewers attach to the segment, <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> recently began testing a light version of its Genuine Draft beer, which has been on the market for about two years. Industry executives and analysts say the nation's weight - and health-consciousness continues to propel the segment's growth `` You can drink the same amount of beer and take in less calories. What more can one ask out of life?'' said <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, who follows the beer industry for <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The light beers typically have a third fewer calories than the 140-150 calories in regular beers and slightly less alcohol. Beverage industry analysts say another important ingredient in the success of light beers has been the ability of brewers to make and market a drink that traditional beer drinkers are n't ashamed to order. In the 1960s, industry watchers said light beers had been pitched mainly as diet drinks for women. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellas </PERSON>, president of the research firm <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the country was n't ready for a low-calorie approach then. Pitching the drink to women may also have alienated some men, which is something brewers normally try to avoid since men reportedly consume about 80 percent of all the beer sold. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, a brewing industry consultant and professor of marketing at the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, said another flaw in the light beers of the 1960s was taste. `` They were horrible, and usually died a fast death. They did n't taste like beer and were poorly marketed,'' he said Milwaukee-based <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> began to turn that around in 1973 when it started testing a new light beer under the Lite name it bought from another brewer. `` Everything you always wanted in a beer ... and less,'' was the original theme. The brewer used former athletes and celebrities to sell its beer, an approach that it continues to use 15 years later. The approach infuriated critics who said it encouraged young people to drink, but it helped <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> convince customers that it was acceptable for tough guys to drink light beer. Others brewers were skeptical about <PERSON> Lite </PERSON>'s chances and stayed out of that end of the market for a few years. `` It was the only significant consumer packaged good industry where a company could bring out imaginative new products and not have competitors follow suit immediately,'' <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> said. By the time others woke up, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> had a grip on the market that it has been slow to yield. `` We will never enjoy that kind of competitive advantage again,'' admitted <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertini </PERSON>. Beverage Marketing said 45.1 million barrels of light beer were sold last year, up 7.1 percent from the previous year, while sales of all kinds of beer slipped 0.2 percent to 187.2 million barrels. There are about 70 light brands. Sales of <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Lite </PERSON> were flat at about 19.3 million barrels, but it is the second-best selling beer overall -LRB- Budweiser is No. 1 at about 50 million barrels -RRB- and holds a 2-to-1 lead in share of the light beer segment. Its main competition comes from Bud Light from <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, which sold an estimated 8.6 million barrels last year, and from <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, which sold 7.9 million barrels. Beverage Marketing estimates Lite held 42.8 percent of the light segment in 1987 compared with 19.1 percent for Bud Light and 17.5 percent for Coors Light. Bud Light has grown at a furious pace since its introduction in 1982, scoring well in consumer surveys with ads that show quirky responses to customers who ask for a `` light'' without specifying the brand and with commercials featuring party animal Spuds MacKenzie. Coors Light, introduced in 1977, has been advertised as the silver bullet that `` wo n't slow you down'' and `` the right beer now.'' Last year, its sales surpassed those of Coors premium beer for the first time. Other leading light beers include Michelob Light at 5.8 percent of the market and Natural Light at 5.1 percent from <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> has captured about 6.2 percent of the market with two brands, <ORGANIZATION> Old </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> and Stroh Light. Light beer accounted for 24.1 percent of overall beer sales in 1987, up from 13.1 percent in 1980. Can its share growth continue? <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> said the increasing incidence of brewers attaching their regular brands' names to light beers show brewers are taking the segment seriously even if they are doing so partly just to get more shelf space. Others say as the median age of the population moves higher, even more people will find themselves worrying about their weight. `` Thirty percent of the market does n't seem to be unattainable,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>, executive editor of the industry newsletter Beer Marketers Insights. `` But can it get to 40 percent, I just do n't know.''
